<div class="vte plainlinks" style="font-size:smaller; text-align:center;"><a href="./Template:Conspiracynav" title="Template:Conspiracynav">v</a> - <a href="./Template_talk:Conspiracynav" title="Template talk:Conspiracynav">t</a> - <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="../w/index.php?title=Template:Conspiracynav&amp;action=edit">e</a></div>
</td></tr></table>The <b>Cloward-Piven strategy</b> was a blueprint for making massive disruptions in the <a href="https://rationalwiki.org/wiki/Welfare" title="Welfare" class="mw-redirect">welfare</a> system of the <a href="https://rationalwiki.org/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>, thus clearing the way toward reforming the system along lines more politically palatable to the authors of the strategy.
<p>The strategy was outlined in an article in <i><a href="https://rationalwiki.org/wiki/The_Nation" title="The Nation" class="mw-redirect">The Nation</a></i> in 1966, many years before the term "welfare reform" became <a href="https://rationalwiki.org/wiki/Political_correctness" title="Political correctness">politically incorrect</a>.
</p>
